04609nam a22006255i 9780226661308DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226661308  a(DE-B1597)535627  a(OCoLC)1134855083  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a001.092221 aGunnell, John G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConventional Realism and Political Inquiry :bChanneling Wittgenstein /cJohn G. Gunnell. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Representational Philosophy and Conventional Realism -- t2. Mentalism and the Problem of Concepts -- t3. The Realistic Imagination in Political Inquiry: The Case of International Relations -- t4. The Challenge to Representational Philosophy: Wittgenstein, Ryle, and Austin -- t5. Contemporary Anti- representationalism: Sellars, Davidson, Putnam, McDowell, and Dennett -- t6. Presentation and Representation in Social Inquiry -- t7. Conventional Realism -- t8. The Quest for the Real and the Fear of Relativism -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen social scientists and social theorists turn to the work of philosophers for intellectual and practical authority, they typically assume that truth, reality, and meaning are to be found outside rather than within our conventional discursive practices. John G. Gunnell argues for conventional realism as a theory of social phenomena and an approach to the study of politics. Drawing on Wittgenstein’s critique of “mentalism” and traditional realism, Gunnell argues that everything we designate as “real” is rendered conventionally, which entails a rejection of the widely accepted distinction between what is natural and what is conventional. The terms “reality” and “world” have no meaning outside the contexts of specific claims and assumptions about what exists and how it behaves. And rather than a mysterious source and repository of prelinguistic meaning, the “mind” is simply our linguistic capacities. Taking readers through contemporary forms of mentalism and realism in both philosophy and American political science and theory, Gunnell also analyzes the philosophical challenges to these positions mounted by Wittgenstein and those who can be construed as his successors.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPolitical science-Philosophy. 0aWittgenstein, Ludwig,-1889-1951. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aConventional Realism.  aLudwig Wittgenstein.  aMind, Reality, and World.  aPolitical Science.  aPolitical Theory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2020z9783110704594oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226661308423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226661308/original  a978-3-11-069309-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070472-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2020  aZDB-23-PLWb2020